11.3 Formal Definition of a Limit Being Infinity
Definition: (Formal definition of a limit being infinity)
Let f (x) be a function defined on an open interval D that contains c, except possibly at x = c.
Then we say that
limx→c
f (x) = ∞
if, for every ε, there exists a δ > 0 such that for all x ∈ D with
0 < |x −c| < δ,
we have
f (x) > ε
.
When this holds we write
limx→c
f (x) = ∞
or
f (x) → ∞
as
x → c
.
Similarly, we say that
limx→c
f (x) = −∞
if, for every ε, there exists a δ > 0 such that for all x ∈ D with
0 < |x −c| < δ,
we have
f (x) < ε
.
When this holds we write
limx→c
f (x) = −∞
or
f (x) → −∞
as
x → c
.
