15.2.2 Physics Example II: Harmonic Oscillator
Figure 29: An undamped spring-mass system is a simple harmonic oscillator.
If the displacement of a simple harmonic oscillator from equilibrium is given by x, and it is released from its maximum displacement A at time t = 0, then the position at later times is given
by
x(t) = Acos(ωt),
where = 2 /T is the angular frequency and T is the period of oscillation. The velocity, v, being the
first time derivative of the position can be computed with the chain rule:
119
Chain Rule
v(t) =
d x
d t Definition of velocity in one dimension
=
d
d t Acos(ωt) Substitute x(t)
= A
d
