18.3 Logarithmic differentiation
We can use the properties of the logarithm, particularly the natural log, to differentiate more difficult functions, such a products with many terms, quotients of composed functions, or functions
with variable or function exponents. We do this by taking the natural logarithm of both sides,
re-arranging terms using the logarithm laws below, and then differentiating both sides implicitly,
before multiplying through by y.
