+ x0
This value of x we feel should be a better guess for the value of x where f (x) = 0. We choose to call
this value of x1, and a little algebra we have
x1 = x0 −
f (x0)
f
0
(x0)
.
If our intuition was correct and x1 is in fact a better approximation for the root of f (x), then our
logic should apply equally well at x1. We could look to the place where the tangent line at x1 is
zero. We call x2, following the algebra above we arrive at the formula
x2 = x1 −
f (x1)
f
0
(x1)
.
And we can continue in this way as long as we wish. At each step, if your current approximation is
xn our new approximation will be xn+1 = xn −
f (xn)
f
0
(xn)
.
