A
(ax +b)
k
and
Ax +B
(ax2 +bx +c)
k
.
Exactly how to do this depends on the factorization of Q(x) and we now give four cases that can
occur.
<blockquote style="background: white; border: 1px solid black; padding: 1em;"> Case (a) Q(x) is
a product of linear factors with no repeats. </blockquote>
This means that Q(x) = (a1x +b1)(a2x +b2)...(anx +bn) where no factor is repeated and no factor
is a multiple of another.
For each linear term we write down something of the form A
(ax+b)
