33 Volume of solids of revolution
33.1 Revolution solids
A solid is said to be of revolution when it is formed by rotating a given curve against an axis.
For example, rotating a circle positioned at (0,0) against the y-axis would create a revolution solid,
namely, a sphere.
33.1.1 Calculating the volume
Calculating the volume of this kind of solid is very similar to calculating any VOLUME1
: we calculate the basal area, and then we integrate through the height of the volume.
Say we want to calculate the volume of the shape formed rotating over the x-axis the area contained
between the curves f (x) and g (x) in the range [a,b]. First calculate the basal area:
|πf (x)
2 −πg (x)
