Vector Addition
Vector Addition is often called tip-to-tail addition, because this makes it easier to remember.
The sum of the vectors you are adding is called the resultant vector, and is the vector drawn from the
initial point (tip) of the first vector to the terminal point (tail) of the second vector. Although they
look like the arrows, the pointy bit is the tail, not the tip. (Imagine you were walking the direction
the vector was pointing... you would start at the flat end (tip) and walk toward the pointy end.)
It looks like this:
298
Two-Dimensional Vectors
Figure 65: Tip-to-tail addition
(Notice, the black lined vector is the sum of the two dotted line vectors!)
Numerically:
