Dot Product
The dot product, sometimes confusingly called the scalar product, of two vectors is given by:
u· v = ux vx +uy vy
or which is equivalent to:
u· v = |u||v|cosθ
where θ is the angle difference between the two vectors. This provides a convenient way of finding
the angle between two vectors:
cosθ =
u· v
|u||v|
52.1.6 Applications of Scalar Multiplication and Dot Product
Unit Vectors
A unit vector is a vector with a magnitude of 1. The unit vector of u is a vector in the same
direction as u, but with a magnitude of 1:
Figure 67: Unit vector
301
Vectors
The process of finding the unit vector of u is called normalization. As mentioned in scalar multiplication, multiplying a vector by constant C will result in the magnitude being multiplied by C.
We know how to calculate the magnitude of u. We know that dividing a vector by a constant will
divide the magnitude by that constant. Therefore, if that constant is the magnitude, dividing the
vector by the magnitude will result in a unit vector in the same direction as u:
w =
u
|u|
, where
w
is the unit vector of
u
