55.3.3 Linear equations
A linear first order differential equation is a differential equation in the form
a(x)
d y
d x
+b(x)y = c(x)
Multiplying or dividing this equation by any non-zero function of x makes no difference to its
solutions so we could always divide by a(x) to make the coefficient of the differential 1, but writing
the equation in this more general form may offer insights.
At first glance, it is not possible to integrate the left hand side, but there is one special case. If b
happens to be the differential of a then we can write
a(x)
d y
d x
