The addition of two complex numbers is just the addition of two vectors, and multiplication by a
fixed complex number can be seen as a simultaneous rotation and stretching.
Multiplication by i corresponds to a counter-clockwise rotation by 90° (/2 radians). The geometric
content of the equation i
2 = &minus;1 is that a sequence of two 90 degree rotations results in a
180 degree ( radians) rotation. Even the fact (&minus;1) · (&minus;1) = +1 from arithmetic can be
understood geometrically as the combination of two 180 degree turns.
All the roots of any number, real or complex, may be found with a simple algorithm. The nth roots
