If the matrix is viewed as a transformation of the plane, then the transformation rotates points
through an angle equal to the argument of the complex number and scales by a factor equal to
the complex number’s absolute value. The conjugate of the complex number z corresponds to the
transformation which rotates through the same angle as z but in the opposite direction, and scales in
the same manner as z; this can be represented by the transpose of the matrix corresponding to z.
401
Complex Numbers
If the matrix elements are themselves complex numbers, the resulting algebra is that of the quaternions. In other words, this matrix representation is one way of expressing the Cayley-Dickson
construction of algebras.
