61.0.1 Calculus/Choosing delta
This page is an addendum to CALCULUS/FORMAL DEFINITION OF THE LIMIT1
.
Recall the definition of a limit:
A number L is the limit of a function f(x) as x approaches c if and only if for all numbers ² > 0 there
exists a number δ > 0 such that
¯
¯
f (x)−L
¯
¯ < ²
whenever
0 < |x −c| < δ.
In other words, given a number ² we must construct a number δ such that assuming
0 < |x −c| < δ
we can prove
¯
¯
f (x)−L
¯
¯ < ²;
moreover, this proof must work for all values of ² > 0.
Note: this definition is not constructive -- it does not tell you how to find the limit L, only how to
check whether a particular value is indeed the limit. We use the informal definition of the limit,
experience with similar problems, or theorems (L’Hopital’s rule, for example), to determine the
value, and then can prove the correctness of this value using the formal definition.
Example 1: Suppose we want to find the limit of f(x) = x + 5 as x approaches c = 9. We know that
the limit L is 9+5=14, and desire to prove this.
We choose δ = ² (this will be explained later). Then, since we assume
|x −9| < δ
1 Chapter 11 on page 79
403
Appendix
we can show
|(x +5)−14| = |x −9|
< δ
= ²
,
which is what we wanted to prove.
We chose δ by working backwards from the formula we are trying to prove:
¯
